<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-566  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 566.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  May 1989 v6 n5 p79(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New challenge to character terminals. (the impact of X Windows)(includes related article on X alternatives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brunet, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>X Windows-based terminals are expected to replace characterterminals as the desktop standard within the next few years, withthe X terminal market expected to grow to $150 million by 1992.andP;  XWindows will give X terminals such features as ability to run on anetwork, graphics interface, UNIX (and DOS) applications on anetworked host, concurrent access of multiple applications onmultiple hosts, and graphical interfaces.andP;  Every UNIX vendorexcept Next Inc has adopted X Windows.andP;  X Windows-based terminalsoffer such advantages as small footprint, no fan, off-loading ofdisplay processing, and low system management requirements.andP;  Xterminals from Acer Counterpoint Inc, Esprit Systems Inc, GraphOnCorp, Network Computing Devices, and Visual Technology Inc arebriefly described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     X Windows (Standard)TrendsMarket AnalysisVDTsCompetitionOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   X terminal comparison chart shows specifications. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>